{In this chapter we will take a first glance at the position after} 1. e4 e5 2.
Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 {. This is the most interesting and strongest move;
White is building up to enforce 5 d4, which will give him the superiority in
the centre. This is a strategically more aggressive strategy than the symmetry
of the previous chapter, and the source from which the need for real opening
theory on the Italian Game stems.} -- ({
Black can meet 4 c3 is a variety of ways, where} 4... Nf6 {is the strongest.})
({According to current theory Black can also equalise with} 4... Qe7 {
, but I think this is less than obviously certain. Actually, in the games
below, I will go as far as to claim an advantage for White in all lines.}) ({
In this chapter we shall also have a quick look at a line which, in grandmaster
play, achieves only equality, but is successful lower down. After} 4... Nf6 5.
d4 exd4 6. e5 {
many games have continued with moves other than the absolutely essential} d5 $1
{, which equalises at once.}) (4... -- {Summary: To conclude quickly on the
material in this chapter: after 4 c3 then 4...Qe7 has a good reputation, but
probably unjustly. Alekhine-Tarrasch and Tyomkin-Zugic contain some ideas
leading to an advantage for White, which should be of practical importance to
anyone playing the Italian Game. --- In the last two games of the chapter we
investigate Sveshnikov's pet line with 6 e5, which is theoretically quite
harmless. Obviously the Russian grandmaster plays this because he feels that
he gets good practical chances, but against a well-prepared opponent this is
probably not the case. But then again, how many people are prepared for every
obscure line after 1 e4 e5 - ? Not many I suppose...}) *

