1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 5. c3 Ba5 {The retreat with 5...Ba5
is perhaps the most natural answer to the Evans Gambit. The bishop remains on
the e1-a5 diagonal, pinning the c3 and d2 pawns for the moment and, more
importantly, is not in any kind of trouble on a5. On the minus side White will
be able to put pressure on the black position with Ba3 later on. Black is
clearly planning to meet this with ...d7-d6. Black will establish a strong
point on e5 and try to keep the centre closed for as long as is reasonably
possible.} ({The retreat} 5... Ba5 {was apparently first played in a not very
correct correspondence game back in 1826 between Evans and McDonnell. This
entertaining game resulted in a win for White after the following:} 6. O-O d6
7. d4 Bg4 8. Qb3 Qd7 9. Ng5 Nd8 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Ba3 Nh6 12. f3 Bb6+ 13. Kh1
Bh5 14. Rd1 Qc8 15. Rxd8+ $2 ({instead, the alternative} 15. Qb5+ {would have
on very quickly for White, while after the much better defence 16...Qf6! Black
would have survived and been in the game}) 15... Qxd8 16. Nxf7 Qh4 $2 17. Qb5+
c6 18. Qxe5+ Kd7 19. Qe6+ Kc7 20. Bd6# {.}) 6. -- ({
In this chapter we shall look at 5.. .Ba5 lines where White refrains from} 6.
d4 {. which is the subject of Chapter 9.}) ({Generally this means} 6. O-O {
, which is covered in Chigorin-Steinitz and the four subsequent games}) ({or} 
6. Qb3 $5 {, as in the first game below.}) (6. -- {Summary: The games
presented in this chapter indicate that Black has several sound ways of
meeting 6 0-0, one of them being the 'Lasker Defence' with 6...d6 7 d4 Bb6. I
believe that the main reason for this is that the advantages for White of
having castled are slightly more long term than those of an immediate attack
on the black centre with 6 d4 (as in the next chapter). Therefore I do not
feel that the lines with 6 0-0 are truly dangerous for Black.}) *

