{In this chapter we shall examine the positions arising after} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3
Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 5. c3 Ba5 6. d4 {. This is Howard Staunton's idea,
which has the advantage that White can avoid Lasker's Defence (as seen in
Chapter 8) by answering} d6 {with something other than} 7. O-O {. Basically
White is putting time over material, which is of course a risky strategy. But
as they say... he who risks nothing gains nothing.} (7. -- {Summary: After 5...
Ba5, 6 d4 is the most dangerous line for Black, but it does not seem to
generate enough pressure to guarantee White an advantage. Black should be able
to hold his own with both 6...d6 and the slightly more adventurous 6...exd4 7
0-0 Nge7!. --- Nevertheless, I believe that there is plenty of room for
improvements on both sides, and that the Evans Gambit will prove a dangerous
weapon into the 21st century. Especially when the opponents are not 2700+
super-grandmasters, and have not checked everything with a computer years in
advance. --- So, although the Spanish gives more promise of a theoretical
