1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Be7 4. d4 d6 {
This is the other main line of the Hungarian Defence.} 5. dxe5 {Usually, books
claim that White has an advantage by entering the endgame, but a closer look
shows that the strongest players do not find any real advantage there at all,
and often soon concede a draw.} ({Therefore we shall look at the more ambitious
} 5. d5 {in the next game}) ({while} 5. Nc3 {is seen in Sveshnikov-Kholmov.})
5... dxe5 6. Qxd8+ Bxd8 7. Bd5 {This game is an example of how Black can win
with this line, even against a strong opponent. Ian Rogers is a famous
attacking player, but clearly less dangerous once the queens comes off. By
creating weaknesses in his own position, White slowly makes the position
difficult for himself, though he could have probably made a draw all the way
to the end. Other options for White are:} (7. Bb5 Bd7 8. O-O Bf6 9. c3 Nge7
10. Be3 Nc8 11. Nbd2 {
½-½ R.Kuczynski-M.Krasenkow, Polish Championship 1996.}) (7. Ng5 Bxg5 8.
Bxg5 Nd4 9. Na3 Be6 10. O-O-O Bxc4 11. Nxc4 f6 12. Be3 O-O-O 13. c3 Nc6 14.
Rxd8+ Nxd8 15. a4 {gave White a slight edge in L.Yudasin-Y.Lapshun, New York
(rapid) 2004, but the a game ended in a draw. It is very hard to win such a
symmetrical position.}) (7. Nc3 $1 {
is clearly the main line, when Black has tried a lot of different moves:} -- (
7... Nf6 8. Be3 $1 O-O (8... Ng4 9. Bd2 O-O 10. h3 Nf6 11. O-O-O {was better
r White in Y.Yakovich-A.Kovalev, Gistrup 1996; Black is not ready to face a
Nd5 jump}) 9. Bc5 Re8 10. Ng5 Be6 11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. Bb5 Nd7 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14.
Ba3 Nb6 15. b3 {
White had an enjoyable advantage in E.Vasiukov-F.Gheorghiu, Manila 1974.}) (
7... f6 8. a3 Nge7 {(generally I find this way of developing dubious)} 9. Be3
Bg4 10. O-O-O Nc8 11. Rd3 Nd6 12. Ba2 Be7 13. Nd2 O-O-O 14. f3 {and White was
better and eventually won in D.Bronstein-V.Kozlov, Daugavpils 1978.}) (7...
Nge7 8. Be3 Ng6 9. O-O-O O-O 10. h3 Na5 11. Be2 Be6 12. Ng5 Bc4 {
, was V.Stoica-V.Hort, Porz 1991, and here maybe} 13. Bg4 $1 {
gives White a real plus.}) (7... Bg4 $5 {looks respectable, e.g.} 8. Be3 Nf6 9.
Bb5 Nd7 10. O-O-O Ncb8 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Bxd7+ {
½-½ A.Shirov-D.Campora, Biel 1995.})) 7... Nge7 8. Bb3 f6 9. c3 Na5 10.
Ba4+ Kf7 11. Nbd2 Be6 12. b4 $5 {
This move is rather committal and doesn't really achieve a lot.} Nc4 13. Nxc4
